metadata.name: Ichigo #127
metadata.description:
This generator is named 'Ichigo' (苺/ いちご), the Japanese word for 'strawberry'. 

Seeing each iteration from a suitable distance, small dots (to me, reminiscent of strawberry seeds) overlay different sequences of geometric repetitions, implying a sense of texture, grittiness and irregularity. 

By looking closer however, it becomes apparent to the viewer that the majority of the composition is in fact government by orderly elements, in this case grids of dots. 

This discovery invites the viewer to consider the output in front of them at different levels, near and far. At what point do you feel the dots begin to dissolve into a texture? When do you stop noticing the dots and instead begin to perceive the overall composition?

These questions are posed in a similar fashion as with meditation; at what point does something become something else? When does an in-breath become an out-breath and vice versa? 

Contemplation on simple questions like these can open a small portal into stillness and mindfulness by taking time to slowly observe our responses. 

23 palettes are included, each named after different areas of Tokyo. 

Press 'S' to download a full size 6000px x 6000px PNG output. 

As always, much gratitude and enjoy your piece.

metadata.name: Nanopanorama #21
metadata.description:
Distorted noise with weird textures and funky shapes rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm.

4671 characters of pure Javascript, no libraries.

Some options can be changed via the URL:

&lw=.25 : The linewidth in millimetres.
&d=.4 : Line density (multiplier to linewidth).
&h=235 : Page height in millimetres. The aspect ratio is 16:9, for a width of 420mm, suitable for A3 plotting.
&bg=1 : Set to 0 to remove background rectangle (recommended for plotting).

When plotting, it is recommended to use a path reordering / optimizing tool such as axicli or vpype to greatly reduce the plotting time.

metadata.name: The String #4
metadata.description:
|| Anniversary project for FX(hash) 1st birthday ||

Each virtual object consists of 365 lights.
Each light represents one day of the year.

We go through every single day, thinking it's all crucial. Yet, from a perspective, it all gets compressed into a single thread. Some of the events are brighter and more memorable. Others just blend or fade away.

I welcomed November 2021 with huge excitement and celebration. The joyful beginning of the month was followed by weeks of misery, anxiety, denial, and acceptance. It was a hard time, but in the long run, it was liberating and started a process of change. Change that happens dynamically to this day.

I couldn't join you last year, but I'm celebrating with you today!



In memory of my Dad.



Donations:
40% – Savepakistan - Flood Relief Fundraiser
10% – Three.js

metadata.name: September #191
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: a working theory #47
metadata.description:
Initial conditions are stated, and then the particles set in motion - the root of generative art. My goal with this piece was to create an illustration that seemed to be from an earlier (or perhaps later?) time; not, at any rate, our current moment. The background is a very subtle gradient; then it is heavily stippled, and followed with a particle system to create more subtle texture. (Look for the very small "hairs" in the background; they are more obvious on the dark ones. They are a subset of the main particle system.) 

Following that, the main particle system is run in real time; I like to "show my work" for generative pieces, as any collector of my previous mints knows, and this is no exception. "Run" your mint for an animated drawing experience. Note that fxpreview() hits a few frames before the end of the full run. I did it this way to ensure a consistent preview. As a result, the preview and the final image will be slightly different, only because the final image has a slightly longer lifespan. 

There are multiple "special" modes, each with a 10% likelihood: 

"spiral" will rotate the canvas as the particle system is running.
"chaos" uses random X/Y vectors during the acceleration phase, rather than X or Y.
"occasionals" adds random large particles in an opposing color.

In addition, there are three possible shapes:

"circle" draws circles for the particles.
"square" draws squares for the particles.
"jagged" draws mostly circles, with a 0.01% chance of a square at a 45 degree angle. 

Finally, there is a non-attribute feature, where the entire piece is drawn at a 45 degree angle. This has a 20% likelihood, but is only apparent on pieces that have no special, or the "occasional" special. Working the math out, you have a 16% likelihood for getting a piece at a noticeable 45 degree angle. 

All main colors have an equal likelihood, but the light background is only 20%.

metadata.name: Resorting #6
metadata.description:
The idea of living within close proximity to nature has enticed people for centuries, especially for the ones used to living in bustling cities. Just picturing a cozy resort in the countryside, or playing music that resembles the feelings of holiday-making can drive us to go on a well-deserved vacation. Even when we don’t know where to, or whether we have the time or resources to slip out of our busy days, or even if that destination exists only in our imaginations. But when we do entertain ourselves with such ideas, we feel like we have taken a step to heal ourselves or to give our mind a worthy time out.

On the other hand, we have been living in human-focused settlements like cities for around 10,000 years, and we have all we need in an urban landscape, yet the idea of living in a secluded resort close to nature kept inviting us. This begs the question: were we supposed to live adjacent to nature to live well? Is it in our nature that we are wired to go back to the world beyond our doors? Or was it because we are aware of how big nature is, and how little time and resources we have to explore them all?

------------
Press [s] to save captured image
------------
It may take a few seconds to render, depending on the device.

created using WEBGL on p5.js

metadata.name: looking through a glass #36
metadata.description:
or life is a colorful mess
or not your usual generative forest

this art project continues the path that 'life is a (beautiful) mess' began with the representation of our lives using drawing lines that make repetitive patterns
as life develops, we look at it through the glass of our unique existence. every event, emotion and thought we experience stain our personal glass and conditions our regard towards the world that surrounds us
the cercles in every composition, represents that glass that we all have between us and the world, and the movement of the lines under it, life developing as we observe it
or it's just another figurative generative art project, as you wish...

10 different palettes
over 30 different color pens
single or multiple color glasses or cercles option
press [1], [2], [3], [4] keys to multiply resolution and reload the piece
press [s] to capture an image .png
press [r] to reload the animation
click the mouse to stop the drawing
doubleclick the mouse to resume the drawing

generative art created by mehno using p5js
